How clangs workflow is:

when we want to create an .o file.

- (clang/lib/tools/driver.cpp) clang_main figures out what mode it is and calls ExecuteCC1Tool.
- (clang/lib/tools/driver.cpp) ExecuteCC1Tool figures out what tool we want and then calls cc1_main.
- (clang/tools/driver/cc1_main.cpp) cc1_main initializes and creates the CompilerInstace and calls ExecuteCompilerInvocation with it.
- (clang/lib/FrontendTool/ExecuteCompilerInvocation.cpp) ExecuteCompilerInvocation eventually calls CreateFrontendAction with the CompilerInstance
- (clang/lib/FrontendTool/ExecuteCompilerInvocation.cpp) CreateFrontendAction calls CreateFrontendBaseAction
- (clang/lib/FrontendTool/ExecuteCompilerInvocation.cpp) CreateFrontendBaseAction switch cases what ProgramAction we want.
  - For example in clang/include/clang/Frontend/FrontendOptions.h we have enum ActionKind and EmitObj, which emits an object file.
  - Here the switch case would create a EmitObjAction.
  - The EmitObjcAction is defined in clang/include/clang/CodeGen/CodeGenAction.h
    - It inherits from CodeGenAction, which in turn inherits from ASTFrontendAction.
- (clang/lib/FrontendTool/ExecuteCompilerInvocation.cpp) This EmitObjAction action is returned up to ExecuteCompilerInvocation. We then call the CompilerInstance with ExecuteAction, giving it the action. 
- (clang/lib/Frontend/CompilerInstance.cpp) CompilerInstaces ExecuteAction eventually calls the three following things
  - Action BeginSourceFile
  - Action Execute
  - Action EndSourceFile
  - These are the generic actions that define the entire workflow.
- (clang/lib/Frontend/FrontendAction.cpp) The BeginSourceFile is called on the EmitObjcAction (inheritance chain is EmitObjcAction->CodeGenAction->ASTFrontendAction->FrontendAction). The top most parent FrontendAction handles this call.
  - This does a bunch of things, but most importantly for us, it calls setASTConsumer on the CompilerInstance.
    - This creates the consumer that will act on the parsed AST.
    - This is created by calling CreateWrappedASTConsumer, which calls CreateASTConsumer.
     - (clang/lib/CodeGen/CodeGenAction.cpp) CreateASTConsumer is overriden by the CodeGenAction.
       - Here it creates our BackendConsumer and returns it.
  - (clang/lib/Frontend/FrontendAction.cpp)  So now BeginSourceFile can set the backendConsumer as the ASTConsumer in the CompilerInstance object
- (clang/lib/Frontend/CompilerInstance.cpp) We then move on to the Execute, which is implemented in the FrontendAction parent
  - (clang/lib/Frontend/FrontendAction.cpp) in Execute, we calls ExecuteAction, which will invoke the CodeGenAction parent.
  - (clang/lib/CodeGen/CodeGenAction.cpp) In ExecuteAction, we will call ASTFrontendActions ExecuteAction (parent) if we arent parsing IR (which we are not in my example).
   - (clang/lib/Frontend/FrontendAction.cpp) Final ExecuteAction, this will call createSema on the compilerInstace. This creates the semantic analysis that is needed when parsing the AST.
   - It then calls ParseAST with the sema (which contains the BackendConsumer).
- (clang/lib/Parse/ParseAST.cpp) Creates the parser and executes it. It then gets the BackendConsumer and calls HandleTranslationUnit on it.
- (clang/lib/CodeGen/CodeGenAction.cpp) The HandleTranslationUnit is what then processes the ASTContext, generates IR and performs passes on it. It also produces the final o file (I think).
- EndSourceFile cleans up


